Quick Installation Instructions
-------------------------------

	There is no automated install process available for The Cog
Engine, so a manual install is necessary. The engine itself is merely a
series of java class files, you will need some sort of game data file in
order to actually try out the engine. "The Cycon Odyssey" is provided for
this purpose. The Cycon Odyssey is currently an incomplete game, but there
is enough in place for a new user to get a feel for how the engine works.
e
1) Download the class files for the Cog Engine (You may optionally
download the source files, and compile them yourself, though this is not
stricly necessary)

2) Download the sample game files for the Cycon Odyssey. You will probably
need the Images archive as well.

3) Extract downloaded files into the directory. The "Images" archive
should be a subdirectory of this directory.

4) Load the "CogEngine.html" file into your favorite web browser, or the
Java Appletviewer.


Example (Under Linux):

tar xvzf CogEngine-0.95-classes.tar.gz
tar xvzf CyconOdyssey-0.95-data.tar.gz
tar xvzf CyconOdyssey-0.95-images.tar.gz
cp CogEngine-0.95/* CyconOdyssey-0.95
cd CyconOdyssey-0.95
appletviewer CogEngine.html



	You can make your own games by following the format of the Cycon
Odyssey text files, but a better solution is to wait for the Cog
Development Application to be finished and released, which should happen
before the Fall of 2001. You can also check out screenshots of this
program at the Cog Engine website, and you can check the source out of our
anonymous CVS repository on sourceforge (see links below).


